{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_zztop_ver01/data/sn95079154/00175032733/1908010901/0216.xml":{"full_text":"TOTEIi REPUBLICAN\nPUBLISHED EVERY THURSDAY AT\nTAZEWELL, VIRGINIA.\n?BY\nWILLIAM C. PENDLETON,\nEditor and Proprietor.\nSUBSCRIPTIONS\nRepublican, one year, in advance $100\nOn Time. 1.50\nAdvertising Rates furnished on ap?\nplication. Correspondence solicited.\nThe publisher of The Repubucan is\nnot responsible for opinions expressed\nby Correspondents.\nThe Republican is entered at the\nPostoffice at Tazewell. Virginia, as\nsecond-class matter.\nTHURSDAY, JANUARY 9, 1908.\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK.\nFrom present indications the business\noutlook for 1908 in the United States is\ngood. For the past few months then*\nwas considerable apprehension among\nbusiness men, this condition being\ncaused by the Wall Street or \"gamblers'\npanic.\" Conditions, however, are now\nrapidly changing. Factories, mills an?l\nfurnaces that had shut down have re?\nsumed and are resuming work, and\nthousands of men that had temporarily\nbeen idle are again at work.\nMany opinions have been expressed\nby public and business men as to what\nwas the cause of the financial strin?\ngency or so-called panic. The very dif?\nficulty that is found in tracing the flurry\nto its true source is positive proof thai\nthere was no legitimate reason for its\norigin. One of its peculiar features is.\nthat it has made but little impression\nupon rural or agricultural districts. The\nfarmers and agricultural labor deem to\nhave been possessed of the usual\namount of currency, and prices for ag?\nricultural products have not b?een ma?\nterially arTected. As long as these con?\nditions contiuue as to agriculture and\nlabor there can be no severe panic; and\nthey are now likely to continue with\nthe resumption that is taking place\namong manufacturers.\nEven though this is what is known as\na Presidential year, we confidently ex?\npect that it will prove a good business\nyear for all the people.\nH. St. George Tuclier announces that\nhe will be a candidate for the Demo?\ncratic nomination for Governor next\nyear. He will only be a candidate.\nThe machine has already fixed the nom?\nination.\nColonel Watterson declares that one\nmore defeat of Mr. Bryan will bring\nthe end of the Democratic party. The\npoor old thing was long ago absorbed\nby Bryanism, and, therefore, no one\nwill know when it dies.\nGovernor Johnson, of Minnesota, has\nundertaken at great length to reply to\nthe New York World's question: \"What\nmust the Democratic party do to win?\"\nHa could have answered that question\nin a few words by saying: \"Ye must\nbe born again.\"\nThe Taft boom seems to be taking\nnew life and gaining in proportions.\nThere is no doubt but that Judge Taft\nis one of the ablest and purest men of\nour country. If he should be chosen\nPresident the American people will find\nhim an able, just and fearless Chief\nExecutive.\nEx-Senator Peyton St Clair, of Gilea\ncounty, we are informed, says that, at\nthe present session of the Legislature,\nthe counties of Giles, Pulaski and Craig\nwill be taken from the Ninth Congress?\nional District and added to the Fifth\nDistrict What do the people of those\ncounties think of that? Will they want\nto leave the Ninth and go where they\nare not wanted?\nThe Richmond News Leader says:\n\"It is pleasant to observe that in the\nVirginia country newspapers there is no\nnote of pessimism. Why should there\nbe? There is not a single section in\nVirginia that has not been prospering\nfor the past ten years under a protect?\nive tariff and the present financial pol?\nicy, both of which our esteemed Rich?\nmond contemporary continues to assail.\nWe protest. The William J. Bryans\nof prominence are becoming entirely\ntoo numerous. There is William Jen?\nnings, of Nebraska; William James, of\nFlorida; and now Texas has trotted out\na William John. Every time the Editor\nwrites William J. he will have to ex?\nplain which Bryan he means.?Norfolk\nVirginian-Pilot\nWhat's the use of protesting? You\nknow you have to take your medicine.\nSo, prepare to wreath your face in\n?mile? and look pretty, while you have\nto say tho doom is good.\nWilliam Jennings Bryan is sand to'\nhave earned $75,000 as speaker and lee\nBeset during the year just closed. He\nshoi.ld stick to the platform. The i\nPresidency pays ?>nlv $50,000, and tiien-e\nis little chance of a. Atae. ?Norfolk Vir?\nginian Pilot.\nWell, who thinks that Mr. Bryan will\nnot stick to the platform? You surely\ndo not. His former occupation as an\nactor has made him pietty shrewd\nabout advertising for the platf?>rm; and\nhe knows of no better way to accom?\nplish that than to be a standing candi?\ndate for the Democratic nomination for\nthe Presidency.\nThe Legislature of Virginia is now in i\nsession. Of the one hundred and forty I\nmembers of the House of Delegates\nand Senate, one hundred and eighteen i\narc Dem?crata. So, the Legislature is i\nalmost solidly Democratic. More than\na million dollars of surplus is now in\nthe State Treasury. The people will\nwatch closely to see what disposition\nwill be made of this large surplus. If\nwidely appropriated it can be made of\n??reit service. If not wisely used the\n?people should hold the Legislature to a i\nstrict account. A lot of hungry vul\nturcs assembled at the Capitol while\nthe General Assembly was in session\ntwo years ago. Some of these were\nfed from the public crib. We trust\nthere will be no repetition of those\nscenes.\nThe Lynching Record.\n(Omaha Bee.)\nOne of the newspapers that has \"made\na specialty of keeping track of crimes\nof violence offers the encouraging re?\nport that the lynching record for 1907\nshows a decrease of more than 25 per\ncent in number from last year, particu?\nlar improvement in law observance be?\ning shown in nearly all of the Southern\nStates. The lynching of negroes for al?\nleged assaults upon white women num?\nbered about eighteen for the year, as\ncompared with forty-five last year.\nCredit to this improvement must go\nto the governors of several states, in\neluding ?Covemor Vardaman, of Missis?\nsippi, who have taken a determined\nstand against lynch law and have not\nhesitated to use the state troops to pre?\nvent mob violence. In both the Caro?\nlinas laws have been passed which pro?\nvide that persons accused of participa?\ntion in lynching bees may be tried in\nc?iunties other than that in which the\ncrime was committed. In both states\nthe governors have taken advantage of\nthis provision of the law and have con?\nducted vigorous prosecutions of mob\nleaders, having the cases tried in coun\nties where it was possible to secure jur?\nors who were not in full sympathy with\nthe accused. The conviction by this\nmethod of several prominent citizens\nhas had a wholesome deterrent effect,\nand has served to demonstrate the fact\nthat lynching may be abolished when?\never and wherever officers give proper\nattention to their obligations to secure\nenforcement and observance of the law.\nBusiness Troubles Oyer.\n(Philadelphia Public Ledger.)\nGradually the currency premium, the\nindex at once of bad monetary laws\nand of disordered credit condition, is\nfading to nothing. Cheaper money, as\ngreenbacker theorists and practical\nbankers agree, means better prices for\ncommodities and more confidence in en?\nterprises. The Berlin Imperial Bank\ncontemplates a reduction of discount\nrate. The Bank of England will natur?\nally follow. Gold imports have about\nstopped.\nThese evidences of returning normal\nstate of business depend on each other,\nand all point in the same direction. Lon\nIdon is inquiring for American stocks,\nanother sequence of better grasp of\nconditions. The New Year promises to\nopen upon a consciousness of strength\nthrough the business body. The losses\nof the \"panic of unreason\" are not re?\npaired. They were too severe to be\nquickly followed by any semblance to a\nboom. Yet the most conservative Am?\nerican now feels that the poise of the\nmoney market is restored. If caution\nin operation is the rule for a year, the\npermanent effect will be useful rather\nthan detrimental. The country will\nmore clearly understand itself. As the\nyear closes, the opinion of safe judges\nis that its troubles keep its company in\ndeparture.\n\"The Weekly Oscillator.\"\n(Baltimore Sun.)\n?Captain Richmond P. Hobson, Repre?\nsentative in Congress of the Sixth\nAlabama district, has an acute\nand original intellect and marked indus?\ntry as a legislator. Captain Hobson, we\nlearn from a Washington dispatch, has\ndrawn up a bill providing for the pub?\nlication by the government of an official\ngazette, to disseminate the news of the\nvarious departments of the government.\nThe publication is to be issued weekly,\nand \"oftener if necessary.\" Every\nmember of Congress is to be entitled to\na certain number of copies, to be distri?\nbuted as he pleases. Captain Hobson\nmodestly refrains from suggesting a\nname for the proposed journal. Why\nnot call it the \"Weekly Osculator, or\nthe \"Osculator- As-Of -Osculator,\" or\nthe Osculator- As-Of ten- As-Neces?\nsary?\" That would suggest blissful rec?\nollections to the gallant Alabamian, and\nmight assure frequent contributions\nfrom him.\nThe total weight of the flagpole on\ntop of New York's tallest building; is 6,\n300 pounds. It is ?30 feet high and 612\nabove the ground.\nRepublic Is All Right.\n(New York World.)\nThere is plenty of work for the critic\na\"?l reformer to do; but there was never\nUm vMorruption in politics than now, the\ngovernment is cleaner and better, the1\ntop, Mme is more firmly es'ablished. The\ngreatest danger that threatens Ameri?\ncan institutions comes from the people'\nthemselvef from their g??od nature,\ntheir indifference, their credulity, their\nspathy, thior readiness to be exploited\nby men who make politics a trade.\nThe republic is bound to last as long\nas the people retain the instinct and ca?\npacity for self-government; even the\nthe latent desire for self-government\nIn spite of ?lemagogues, never more elo?\nquent, im: H ntisl, and high-stationed, in\nspite of corrupt ionists; in spite of pre?\ndatory joov? rty. predati ry plutocracy,\nand all the other forces of evil, not only\nare American institutions safe and the\nrepublic secure, but they are safer and\nsecurer than at any oth?;r period in the\nhistory of the United Slate.?.\nLong live thv republic\nFuture Battleships.\n(Scientific American.)\nThe battleship of the future will be of\npre.it size: displacement will be not less\nthini 20,000 tons, and this will increase\nso rapidly that a 30.000-ton ship will\nprobably be afloat before the close of\nthe next decade. The main armament\nwill consist exclusively of heavy guns\nof not less than 12-inch caliber, and un?\nless the difficulty of erosion can be over?\ncome, the 12-inch will give place to a\n13-inch, and possibly to a 14-inch piece.\nFuture engagements will be fought at\nan extreme range, the extent of which\nwill be limited only by the ability of the\nfire control officer to see the fall of the\nshots. The determination of the range\nat which an engagement shall be fought\nwill lie with the fleet which i>ossesse9\nthe faster speed.\nHow's Thli?\nWe Set One llnn.lre.l Holla'? Rewar.l\nf or oinv ciif-e vf catarrh that ???mn -t c\ni-nreol l?v lia1!'? Catarrh Cure.\nF J. CHENEY CO.. Toledo, O.\nWe, the iiv.ljr-o'iineil. have known F ,1.\nCIhhmj for the Un 15 yearp. an?! believe\nhim pertwtlv honorable in all bu-ino-t\ntrouisaetiooiiM f.nd Baaaeiall] o'i> to OStT?\nout any obliintions Bfda hv hip firm.\nW.?I.I0|V4. Kivnan A M*?KVIN,\nWholcaal? liiurjutl?*4s, Toledo, o.\nH?H'p Catarrh Cure i* ???ko-n internally.\nacting ?lirectly upon ihe Mood and tim\nMMM fiirluc?**? I f the ttylaui. Testimoniale\n?put free. I'riiv, 76c per loottle. Sold I?y\nall I)rc.|f|iictf.\nTake Hall's Family Pills f?>r constipa?\nit.?n.\nTacts About Folk?.\nArt objects collected by the late Rich?\nard Mansfield are to be sold during Jan?\nuary at the American Art Gallerits,\nNew York.\nThe curators of the University of\nMissouri have accepted the resignation\nof President R. H. Jessee, tendered on\naccount of ill health.\nOfficial announcement is made by\nRev. Anson Phelps Stoke?, Jr., secre?\ntary of the Yale Corporation, that Wil?\nliam Davis Ely, of Providence, R. I., a\nretired lawyer, is the oldest graduate of\nYale living. This announcement is made\nto settle a dispute.\nThe oldest of the Scottish peers is the\nEarl of Wemyss, who is now in his\neighty-ninth year, and who has lived in\nthe reigns of five sovereigns. He is\nstill a very active man and very fond\nof shooting, fishing and motoring. He\nmakes frequent speeches in the House\nof Lords.\nHenry Hadley, of New York, who is\nin Berlin, directed the Philharmonic Or?\nchestra of that city on Friday evening\nand was cordially received. The orches?\ntra played his new symphony, which\nwill be given in America for the first\ntime in January by the Boston Sym?\nphony Orchestra. Mr. Hadley will di?\nrect the opera at Mainz this winter.\nJames C. Courts, who has just re?\nceived a reappointment as clerk of the\nAppropriations Committee of the House\nof Representatives, is now serving his\nthirtieth year in the service of the\nHouse, having first been appointed by\nRepresentative Atkins, of Tennessee,\nin 1870. He is one of the highest sala?\nried employes in the House.\nA tickling cough, from any cause, is\nquickly stopped by Dr. Shoop's Cough\nCure. And it is so thoroughly harmless\nand safe, that Dr. Shoop tells mothers\neverywhere to give it without limita?\ntion, even to very young babes. The\nwholesome green leaves and tender'\nstems of a lung-healing mountainous\nshrub, furnish the curative properties to\nDr. Shoop's Cough Cure. It calms the\ncough, and heals the sore and sensitive\nbronchial membrances. No opium, np\nchloroform, nothing harsh us??d to in?\njure or suppress. Simply a resinous\nplant extract, that helps to heal aching\nlungs. The Spaniards call this shrub\nwhich the Doctor uses, \"The Sacred\nHerb.\" Always demand Dr. Shoop's\nCough Cure. Sold by Jno. E. Jackson.\nAlonzo Smith, of Showh<?gan, Maine,\nhas an old gun which was used in the\nbattle of Bunker Hill, 131 years ago.\nWilliam Croas, secretary of State in\nOklahoma, signs his name officially\n\"Bill Cross.\"\nTrial ?Catarrh treatments are being\nmailed out free, on request, by Dr.\nShoop, Racine, Wis. These teats are\nproving to the people?without a penny's\ncost?the great value of this scientific\nprescription known to druggists every?\nwhere as Dr. Shoop's Catarrh Remedy.\nSold by Jno. E. Jackson.\nThe state railways of Italy have a\nmileage of about 7,3000 miles, an in?\ncrease of 2,600 miles since 1885.\nSend us your next order for job work\n?we are in a position to do it just a\nlittle better and a little cheaper than\nany other printing office in this section.\nSend for price list\nReligion? Ile??\nSome professed Christians pinch and\nstarve themselves into walking skele?\ntons, and th\"iti try to excuse themselves\non the plea of ill health or \"cci.stitu\ntional\" ailments. The medicines they\nneed arv from Christ's pharmacy. A\nlarge draught of Bible taken every\nmorning, a throwing open of the heart's\nwindows to the pron?is?*s of the Master,\na few words of honest prayer, a deed or\ntwo of kindness to tho next person\nwhom you meet, will do more to bright?\nen your countenance and help your di?\ngestion than all the drugs of the doc?\ntors. If you want to get your aches\nand trials out of sight, hide them under\nyour mercies. ?Theodore L. ?Cuyl?r.\nPeople say that it docs not make any\ndifference whether a man keeps the Ten\nCommandments or not, he will go to\nheaven anyway. If that is the kind of\na place heaven is, it is scarcely worth\nwhile for anybody to go there. It is\nsimply this world over again. For my?\nself, though 1 love my kind and my own\nredemption, I pray nny God to keep\nheaven as it is to change me. xrhange\nthe world, not heaven; to bring me to\nthe feet of the Lord and Savior of heav?\nen and then I shall walk among all the\nstars with their glory undinnme?!. and I\nshall know the meaning of that highest\nof my Lord's beatitudes, \"Blessed are\nthe pure in heart for they shall see\nGod.\" ?Alexander McKenzie.\nCured of Lung Trouble.\n\"It is now eleven years since I had a\nnirrow escape from consumption.\"\nwrites C. O. Floyd, a leading business\nman of Kershaw, S. C. \"I had ran\ndown in weight to 135 pounds, and\ncoughing was constant, both by day and\nby night. Finally I began taking Dr.\nKing s New Discovery, and continued\nthis for about six months, when my\ncough and lung trouble were entirely\ngone and I was restored to my normal\nweight, 170 pounds.\" Thousands of per?\nsons are healed every year. Guaranteed\nat J. E. Jackson's drug store. 50c. ar.d\n$1.00. Trial bottle free.\nJapan and China now use more mer?\ncury than most of the other countries,\nand this is about the only met?l the\nprice of which has decreased of late.\nIn the East it is used for making ver\nmillion, and in .lat?an largely in the com?\npounding of a secret explosive.\nWis-3 Counsel from the South.\n\"I want to give some valuable advice\nto those who suffer with lame back and\nkidney trouble, says J. R. Blanken\nship, of Beck, Tenn. \"1 have proved to\nan al?solute certainty that Electric Hit?\nlers will positively cure this distressing\ncondition. The first bottle gave me\ngreat relief, and after taking a few\nmore bottlat*, 1 was completely cured;so\ncompletely that it becomes a pleasure\nto recommend thi great remedy. Sold\nunder guarantee at John E. Jackson's\ndrug store. Price 50c.\nThe use of the miscroacope in the up?\nright position causes much fatigue. A.\nA. C E. Merlin, an English microscop?\nio, has designed a new eyepiece, which\nhas a prism enabling the observer to\nlook through the tube from the side, in?\nstead of the top.\nHow to Cure Chilblains.\n\"To enjoy freedom from ^chilblains,\"\nwrites John Kemp, East Otisfield, Me.,\n\"I apply Bucklen's Arnica Salve. Have\nalso used it for salt rheum with excell?\nent results.\" Guaranteed to cure fever\nsore*, indolent ulcers, piles, burns,\nwounds, frost bites and skin diseases.\n25c. at John E. Jackson's drug store.\nThe Choco and San Juan districts of\nColombia are very rieh in gold and plat?\ninum, but until they are tapped with\nroutes of communication, over which\nprovisions and machinery can be taken\nto the minea, there is little hope for\ntheir development.\n\"To Keep Well\nThe whole year through,\" writes L. A.\nBartlett, of Rural Route 1, Guilford,\nMe., 1 and my family use Dr. King's\nNew Life Pills. They have proven\nmost satisfactorily to all of us.\" They\ntone the system and cure billiousness,\nmalaria and constipation. Guaranteed\nat John E. Jackson's drug store, 25c.\nCertain kinds of noise attract snakes.\nThe whirr of the mowing machine is\none, and in six months as many as 120\ncobras alone have been killed on a grass\nfarm in Indna by the advancing machine.\n?Madras Times.\nWhen the Stomach, Heart, or Kidney\nnerves get weak, then these organs al?\nways fail. Don't drug the Stomach, nor\nstimulate the Heart or Kidneys. That\nis simply a makeshift. Get a prescrip?\ntion known to Druggists everywhere as\nDr. Shoop's Restorative. The Restor?\native is prepared expressly for these\nweak inside nerves Strengthen these\nnerves, build them up with Dr. Shoop's\nRestorative?tablets or liquid?and see\nhow quickly help wiln come. Free\nsample test sent on request by Dr.\nShoop, Racine, Wis, Your health is\nsurely worth this simple test. Sold by\nJno. E. Jackson.\nThe Bishop of Bristol, England, in\naddressing an open-air meeting of rail?\nroad men, observed that he was a work?\nman, only he did not get his Saturday\nafternoons and never got a Sunday off.\nThe finest Coffee Substitute ever\nmade, has recently been produced by\nDr. Shoop of Racine Wis. You don't\nhave to boil it twenty minutes or thirty\nTninutes. \"Made in a minute\" says the\ndoctor. \"Health Coffee\" is really the\nclosest Coffee Imitation ever vet pro?\nduced. Not a grain of real Coffee in it\neither. Health Coffee Imitation is\nmade from pure toasted cereals or\ngrains, with malt, nuts, etc. Really it\nwould food an expert?were he to un?\nknowingly drink it for ?Coffee. Sold by\nHarrisson, Barns Co.\nPyocyanse serum, the discovery of\nProfessor Emmerich, of Munich, is\nclaimed to completely destroy diphtheria\nbacilli?even in the severest cases?\nwhen sprayed into the patient's throat.\nRKSUKKD THE GREAT WHITER.\nAmerican Was Not Awed by ?Ireuchy\nPoet Laureate.\nA ?rrlter In Harpers Weekly brings\nto light an Interesting anecdote of\nTennyson which well Illustrates the\nsingular habits of the gr?a; laur?at?\nIn his intercourse with bis friends.\nThe poet was not only brusque and\nrough, but he was domineering and\nexacting, and most other men were\nafraid of htm. But an American\nschoolmaster who for many years\nmaintained a great intimacy with him\nbad no fear In his heart, and sat and\nsmoked on an equality with the eaeer\neign singer by Farrlngford fireside.\n\"One evening,\" says the writer,\n\"when the two were thus toce? her.\nTennyson said that he would derart\nfrom his custom and narrate a i?er\nsonal experience; but he bad sultered\na good deal from repetitions of his\ntales by those to whom be bad told\nthem, and he would be obliged to ask\nhis friend never to repeat what he\nwas about to hear. The American\nsmoked on for a few seconds while\nTennyson waited for the promise, and\nthen he said: 'My lord. In my coun?\ntry a gentleman would never make\nthat request of another gentleman.'\n'II-h-m!' said the poet, and \"poked\nout of eyes that wondered If the\nquiet smoker opposite knew how much\nhe'd said. Then he told the story.\"\nCLEVER SCHEME THAT FAILED.\nOld Salesman's Advice Left Firm\nWorse Off Than Before.\nHenry Clews Is telling a new story\nwhich he says he got straight from\nthe Canal street district, says ?lie\nNew York Times. A young jobbing\nfirm, the tale tells, overbought for\nthe fall trade. Their heaviest mistake\nhad been In the line of overcoats,\nwhich It looked they would have to\ncarry over a season. Efforts to get\ncash for the stock were fruitless, ex?\ncept at ruinous rates. At last the firm\nwent to an old-timer In the trade for\nadvice. \"Well,\" asid the man of ex?\nperience, \"you've got a pretty good\nlist of customers. Just divide the\ncoats up into lots of thirteen each.\nSend a batch apiece to some of your\nsharpest customers, but make out\nthe bills for twelve. They'll be\ntickled to get one coat for nothing\nthat they'll take 'em all.\" The scheme\nhad been tried before the men met\nagain. The old-timer waited for his\npraise. \"Well, didn't they keep the\ncoats?\" he asked. \"Yes.\" returned\nthe Jobber, sadly. \"One each. The one\nthat wasn't billed.\"\nAte Heart of Assassin.\nA correspondent of the North China\nDally News describes what followed\nthe execution of an assassin: \"When\nthe heart of Hsu Hsl-lin was cut out\nof bis body and had been laid before\nths remains of his victim as a sacri?\nfico to the late governor's manes.\nmembers of his bodyguard, to signify\ntheir zeal and hatred of the assassin.\nseized Hsu's still warm heart and\ncutting it up Into mineo meat boiled\nIt and served the grewsome dish\namong themselves to be eaten. This\nseems a poor way of revenging the\ndeath of one patron, especially since\nit was due to the very Ineptitude and\nsubsequent panic of this very hrave\nbodyguard that enabled Hsu iTsl-lln\nto fire so many shots, without any\nkind of hindrance, at the late En\nMin.\"\nHouse Eleven Hundred Years Old.\nSt. Albans possesses the oldest In?\nhabited house in the country. Tl is\ndistinction is said to belong to 'the old\nRound house, now the Fighting Cocks\nInn, which stands close to the River\nVer. It is a curious structure?cf\noctagonal shape?of early Saxon ori?\ngin, having been built as a boatbouae\nto the ancient monastery founded at\nSt. Albans by King Offa about the\nyear 795, and Is thus over 1,100 years\nold. A subterranean passage, now\nblocked up, runs from the basement\nto the ruins of the monastery, a dis?\ntance of about 200 yards. There is a\nshed at the back of the house, where\nIt Is said Oliver Cromwell stabled his\nhorse, himself once sleeping under its\nroof during the civil war.?Collecting.\nHypnotic Sunstroke.\nA German physician who bad a pa?\ntient who could not afford to go to a\nwarm climate, thought he would ac?\ncomplish the same result by means of\nhypnotism. The doctor chalked a pic?\nture of the sun on the celling, and by\nsuggestion Induced the patient to be?\nlieve It really was the sun and that\nIt would cure him. But the patient\nsoon died. When the doctor's friends\nguyed him about the novel treatment\nbe indignantly explained that the pa?\ntient was getting along nicely and\nwould have got well had he not unex?\npectedly died of sunstroke.\nMedical Training for Character.\nAs a school of character it Is doubt?\nful If any better could be devised than\nthe routine career of a medical stu?\ndent. It Is not claimed that every\nmedical student at the end of his five\nyear curriculum will be found to have\nbecome a saint. But if he has not de?\nveloped manly qualities of self-re?\nstraint, courage, gentleness and for?\nbearance, It is not for want of oppor?\ntunity of practicing these virtues.\nEnough and to Spare.\n\"And the name is to be\"?asked the\nsuave minister as he approached the\nfont with the precious armful of fat\nand flounces. \"Augustus Philip Ferdi?\nnand Codrington Chesterfield Livings\nton Snooks.\" \"Dear me!\" Turning to\nthe sexton: \"A little more water, Mr\nPerkins, if you please.\"?Tit-Bits\nMexico has a brewery which has an?\nnual receipts of $6,000,000.\nThe most northerly railway 